Whereas, the State of Texas possesses an area of one hundred and seventy-five million, five hundred and ninety-four thousand acres of Inad, (very little of which is not adapted to agricultural or pasturage purposes) through which her enterprising citizens have in contem-
plation a net work of railroads, four hundred and sixty miles being now in running order, one of which roads commences at the Eastern boundary of the State, running West to Houston, and there connect-
ing with others extending to Galveston; to Columbia, on the Brazos; to the River Colorado, at Columbus; to Brenham, and on the line known as the Central Railroad, extending to the distance of one hundred and forty miles, from the Port of Galveston; none of which railroads have any present connection with those of other States;
